  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses a 5% Phase 1 growth rate and 7% discount rate. But reasonable people disagree on these numbers. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions. Find the combination you believe in.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td class="row-header">{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Because Colgate operates with a lower required rate of return (due to very stable cash flows), the DCF relies heavily on the discount rate. A 1% swing in required return causes significant changes in fair value.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pricing power:</strong> Colgate has successfully passed raw material costs to consumers. If margins structurally improve further, FCF will grow faster than 5%.</li>
    <li><strong>Share repurchases:</strong> Colgate has historically returned capital through buybacks. Reducing the share count over time artificially increases per-share value beyond our static share count model.</li>
    <li><strong>Pet Nutrition growth:</strong> Hill's Pet Nutrition is a significant growth driver. Faster acceleration here could outperform broader consumer staple assumptions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Foreign Exchange headwinds:</strong> As a global company, a strong dollar materially reduces reported revenue and earnings overseas.</li>
    <li><strong>Private label competition:</strong> In inflationary environments, consumers may trade down from premium brands to cheaper private labels, pressuring market share.</li>
    <li><strong>Discount rate compression:</strong> If the risk-free rate rises significantly, requiring a 7% return might be too low, compressing the fair value valuation multiple.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 7% discount rate instead of 10%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents the required return relative to risk. Colgate is a consumer staple with highly predictable cash flows and a very low beta (0.264). According to the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM), a risk-free rate of ~4.2% plus the equity risk premium yields a lower required return for a stock this defensive compared to high-growth tech stocks.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 5% FCF growth when FCF historically fluctuates?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While year-to-year FCF fluctuates with working capital and capital expenditures, Colgate's long-term organic sales growth target is 3-5%. We assume 5% FCF growth over the next five years as margins normalize and pricing actions stick, which is standard for top-tier consumer packaged goods (CPG) companies.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

